      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Active-Active Configuration"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In an active-active setup, a global load balancer distributes traffic across regions. Cloudflare Load Balancing and AWS Route 53 Application Recovery Controller (ARC) are the two most common choices. The key configuration is the health monitor: it must distinguish between a region that is down and one that is slow, because routing 100% of traffic to a degraded-but-live region can cause a cascading failure."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "hcl"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Active-active: Kubernetes multi-cluster traffic split via weighted services\n# Global load balancer (e.g. Cloudflare Load Balancing) routes across clusters.\n# Each cluster's HPA manages its own replica count independently.\n\n# Terraform: Cloudflare Load Balancing pool (illustrative)\nTF_POOL = '''\nresource \"cloudflare_load_balancer_pool\" \"genai_api\" {\n  name = \"genai-api-pool\"\n  origins {\n    name    = \"us-east-1\"\n    address = \"api.genai.us-east-1.internal\"\n    weight  = 0.5\n    enabled = true\n  }\n  origins {\n    name    = \"us-west-2\"\n    address = \"api.genai.us-west-2.internal\"\n    weight  = 0.5\n    enabled = true\n  }\n  health_threshold = 1    # failover when 0 healthy origins remain in pool\n  monitor = cloudflare_load_balancer_monitor.genai_health.id\n}\n\nresource \"cloudflare_load_balancer_monitor\" \"genai_health\" {\n  type     = \"https\"\n  path     = \"/health\"\n  interval = 30\n  retries  = 3\n  timeout  = 5\n  expected_codes = \"200\"\n  expected_body  = \"ok\"\n}\n'''\n\n# On failover: Cloudflare automatically sets the failed origin's weight to 0\n# and routes 100% to the healthy origin. No DNS change or human action required.\n# Recovery: once the failed origin passes health checks again, weight restores.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Weight-based routing: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "normally 50/50. In a planned maintenance window or canary deployment, shift to 10/90 or 0/100 using the load balancer API without changing DNS."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Stateless requirement: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "active-active only works cleanly for stateless requests. If your inference server uses a KV-cache that is session-affined to a specific pod, cross-region requests will bypass that cache and increase latency. Use consistent hashing at the application level to route the same session consistently within a region."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Fine-tuned weight sync: ",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "both regions must have the same fine-tuned weights deployed simultaneously. Coordinate deployments to ensure consistency before shifting traffic to the newly deployed region."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Active-Passive (Warm) with Route 53"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The warm standby strategy keeps the DR region at minimum capacity \u2014 typically 2 pods with weights loaded \u2014 consuming roughly 25% of production-scale GPU cost while providing a 5\u201310 minute RTO. The DNS flip is the critical action in failover:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Warm standby: keep DR region pods loaded; flip Route53 on failure\nimport boto3\n\nr53 = boto3.client('route53')\nPRIMARY_IP  = 'api.genai.us-east-1.internal'\nDR_IP       = 'api.genai.us-west-2.internal'\nZONE_ID     = 'Z1234567890ABC'\nRECORD_NAME = 'api.genai.internal'\n\ndef _upsert_cname(target: str):\n    r53.change_resource_record_sets(\n        HostedZoneId=ZONE_ID,\n        ChangeBatch={'Changes': [{\n            'Action': 'UPSERT',\n            'ResourceRecordSet': {\n                'Name': RECORD_NAME,\n                'Type': 'CNAME',\n                'TTL': 30,\n                'ResourceRecords': [{'Value': target}],\n            },\n        }]},\n    )\n\ndef failover_to_dr():\n    _upsert_cname(DR_IP)\n\ndef failback_to_primary():\n    # Only call after primary passes health checks for 5 consecutive minutes\n    _upsert_cname(PRIMARY_IP)\n\n# Route 53 Application Recovery Controller (ARC) provides a safer alternative:\n# it models routing controls and safety rules to prevent partial failover states.\narc = boto3.client('route53-recovery-control-config', region_name='us-west-2')\n# arc.update_routing_control(RoutingControlArn=..., RoutingControlState='Off')\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Route 53 ARC for production: ",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "For production workloads, use Route 53 Application Recovery Controller instead of direct CNAME manipulation. ARC provides routing controls with safety rules that prevent partial failover states \u2014 for example, preventing failback to the primary while it is still in an unhealthy state. ARC's readiness checks also validate that the DR region has sufficient capacity before allowing a control plane action."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The warm standby pre-scales to full production capacity as soon as the failover trigger fires \u2014 not after DNS flips. This ensures that by the time clients resolve the new DNS entry (after the 30-second TTL expires), the DR region can handle full traffic. Scaling warm standby from 2 to 4+ pods while DNS TTL is draining is the key timing dependency."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Provider-Level Fallback Chain"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For services that use external LLM APIs (OpenAI, Anthropic, Bedrock), a provider failover chain is a separate and complementary layer from region failover. The chain routes to successively lower-priority providers when the primary is unavailable, with a circuit-breaker per provider to avoid hammering a provider that is failing:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# LLM provider router: active + fallback chain with circuit-breaker\nimport time, logging\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom typing import Optional, Callable\n\nlog = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n@dataclass\nclass ProviderConfig:\n    name: str\n    endpoint: str\n    model: str\n    priority: int          # lower = preferred\n    failure_threshold: int = 5   # consecutive failures before circuit opens\n    recovery_seconds: int  = 60  # how long before retrying after circuit opens\n\n@dataclass\nclass CircuitBreaker:\n    provider: ProviderConfig\n    failures: int = 0\n    opened_at: Optional[float] = None\n\n    @property\n    def is_open(self) -> bool:\n        if self.opened_at is None:\n            return False\n        if time.time() - self.opened_at > self.provider.recovery_seconds:\n            # Half-open: allow one probe\n            return False\n        return True\n\n    def record_success(self):\n        self.failures = 0\n        self.opened_at = None\n\n    def record_failure(self):\n        self.failures += 1\n        if self.failures >= self.provider.failure_threshold:\n            self.opened_at = time.time()\n            log.warning('Circuit opened for provider %s', self.provider.name)\n\nclass LLMRouter:\n    def __init__(self, providers: list[ProviderConfig]):\n        self._providers = sorted(providers, key=lambda p: p.priority)\n        self._breakers = {p.name: CircuitBreaker(p) for p in self._providers}\n\n    def complete(self, prompt: str, call_fn: Callable[[ProviderConfig, str], str]) -> str:\n        for provider in self._providers:\n            breaker = self._breakers[provider.name]\n            if breaker.is_open:\n                log.debug('Skipping %s (circuit open)', provider.name)\n                continue\n            try:\n                result = call_fn(provider, prompt)\n                breaker.record_success()\n                return result\n            except Exception as exc:\n                log.warning('Provider %s failed: %s', provider.name, exc)\n                breaker.record_failure()\n        raise RuntimeError('All LLM providers unavailable')\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Configure the priority order based on cost and quality:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Self-hosted model (lowest cost, full control over data residency)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Primary cloud provider (e.g., AWS Bedrock \u2014 fast, managed, no egress concern)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Secondary cloud provider (e.g., OpenAI API \u2014 external dependency, may have data residency implications)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Cached response fallback \u2014 for common, deterministic prompts only"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Model Weight Synchronization Across Regions"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The most common active-passive DR failure mode is not the DNS flip failing \u2014 it is the DR region discovering that the fine-tuned model weights it needs have not been replicated from the primary. S3 Replication handles this automatically, but replication lag and sync failures can leave the DR region one or more model versions behind:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Model weight sync: ensure DR region has all fine-tuned adapters\n# before a disaster occurs.\nimport boto3, subprocess, json\nfrom datetime import datetime\n\nPRIMARY_BUCKET = 'genai-models-us-east-1'\nDR_BUCKET      = 'genai-models-us-west-2'\ns3_primary = boto3.client('s3', region_name='us-east-1')\n\ndef list_production_models() -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"Return all model versions currently deployed to production.\"\"\"\n    resp = s3_primary.list_objects_v2(\n        Bucket=PRIMARY_BUCKET, Prefix='models/production/'\n    )\n    return [obj for obj in resp.get('Contents', [])]\n\ndef verify_dr_sync(model_key: str) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Return True if DR bucket has same ETag as primary.\"\"\"\n    s3_dr = boto3.client('s3', region_name='us-west-2')\n    try:\n        primary_etag = s3_primary.head_object(\n            Bucket=PRIMARY_BUCKET, Key=model_key)['ETag']\n        dr_etag = s3_dr.head_object(\n            Bucket=DR_BUCKET, Key=model_key)['ETag']\n        return primary_etag == dr_etag\n    except s3_dr.exceptions.ClientError:\n        return False\n\ndef audit_dr_sync() -> dict:\n    results = {}\n    for obj in list_production_models():\n        key = obj['Key']\n        synced = verify_dr_sync(key)\n        results[key] = 'synced' if synced else 'MISSING'\n    missing = [k for k, v in results.items() if v == 'MISSING']\n    if missing:\n        print(f'WARNING: {len(missing)} models not synced to DR: {missing}')\n    return results\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Run "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "audit_dr_sync()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " as part of the weekly capacity review (not just when a disaster is declared). If any production model is missing in the DR region, the warm-standby RTO guarantee is invalid because the DR pods will fail to load the correct model version after a failover."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Failback: Returning Traffic to Primary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Failback is as operationally risky as failover. Returning traffic to the primary region before it is fully healthy can cascade a second outage. The failback sequence must be slower and more deliberate than the failover:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Verify primary region passes all health checks for at least 5 consecutive minutes before initiating failback."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Shift 10% of traffic back to primary using load balancer weight adjustment (not DNS change). Monitor for 5 minutes."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If no error rate increase, shift to 50/50. Monitor for 10 minutes."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If stable, complete the shift to 100% primary. Reduce DR region back to minimum warm-standby capacity."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
